Write a Function Used to Evaluate Each Model¶

  • Can Input Any sklearn Model

  • Can choose the amount of runs to run (Default 3), with data re-splited and model re-trained.

  • Will Output the Accuracy / Precision / Recall / F1 score of each run

  • Will Return the average accuracy of the runs

  • Can Select Different Subsets of Data (Default choose all)

  • Can Choose to Scale the Data or Not (Default not to scale)
  • Can draw CONFUSION_MATRIX / ROC Curve
In [7]:
# Test Function to evaluate each model and produce scoring / ROC curve / Confusion matrix
def evalute_model(model, RUNS=3, TAG="TEST MODEL", data_selection="1111111", draw_CONFUSION_MATRIX=False, draw_ROC=False, SCALE=False):
    model_scores = []
    # Run for a number of runs
    for i in range(0,RUNS):
        # Split data into training and testing data
        train_data, test_data = train_test_split(raw_data, test_size=0.3)
        
        LIMIT = ['LIMIT_BAL']
        SEX = ['SEX']
        GENERAL_LIST = ['EDUCATION', 'MARRIAGE']
        AGE = ['AGE']
        PAY = ['PAY_0', 'PAY_2', 'PAY_3', 'PAY_4', 'PAY_5', 'PAY_6']
        BILL_AMT = ['BILL_AMT1', 'BILL_AMT2', 'BILL_AMT3', 'BILL_AMT4', 'BILL_AMT5', 'BILL_AMT6']
        PAY_AMT = ['PAY_AMT1', 'PAY_AMT2', 'PAY_AMT3', 'PAY_AMT4', 'PAY_AMT5', 'PAY_AMT6']

        DATA_LIST = []
        if data_selection[0]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + LIMIT
        if data_selection[1]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + SEX
        if data_selection[2]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + GENERAL_LIST
        if data_selection[3]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + AGE
        if data_selection[4]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + PAY
        if data_selection[5]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + BILL_AMT
        if data_selection[6]=="1":
            DATA_LIST = DATA_LIST + PAY_AMT
        
        # Select the X and Y of the training and testing data
        train_data_X = train_data[DATA_LIST]
        train_data_Y = train_data[['default payment next month']]
        test_data_X = test_data[DATA_LIST]
        test_data_Y = test_data[['default payment next month']]
        
        if SCALE:
            scaler = StandardScaler()
            scaler.fit(train_data_X)
            train_data_X = scaler.transform(train_data_X)
            test_data_X = scaler.transform(test_data_X)
        
        # Fit the current model
        model.fit(train_data_X, train_data_Y.values.ravel())
        
        # Calculate the scores
        run_score = {}
        run_score['score'] = model.score(test_data_X, test_data_Y.values.ravel())
        m_p = model.predict(test_data_X)
        if 0 in m_p and 1 in m_p:
            run_score['precision'] = precision_score(test_data_Y, m_p)
            run_score['recall'] = recall_score(test_data_Y, m_p)
            run_score['f1'] = f1_score(test_data_Y, m_p)
        elif 0 in m_p:
            print("RUN "+str(i+1)+": All predicted labels are 0!")
        else:
            print("All predicted labels are 1!")
        model_scores.append(run_score)
    
    # Print out results
    print("========== "+str(TAG)+" ==========")
    total = 0
    for run in model_scores:
        print("Accuracy: {:>10f} / Precision: {:>10f} / Recall: {:>10f} / F1 Score: {:>10f}".format( \
            run.get('score', 0), run.get('precision', 0), run.get('recall', 0), run.get('f1', 0)))
        total = total + run['score']
    print("AVG SCORE in "+str(RUNS)+" runs: "+str(total/RUNS))
    print("="*(len(TAG)+22))
    
    # Set Return Value
    ret = total/RUNS
              
    # Draw Confusion Matrix if needed
    if draw_CONFUSION_MATRIX:
        # Contriants
        COLOR_MAP = plt.cm.Blues
        CLASSES = ["PAY", "Not PAY"]
        # Calculate Confusion Matrix with and without normalization
        c_m = confusion_matrix(test_data_Y, m_p)
        c_m_norm = c_m.astype('float') / c_m.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        # PLOT Confusion Matrix without normalization
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.imshow(c_m, interpolation='nearest', cmap=COLOR_MAP)
        plt.title(str(TAG))
        plt.colorbar()
        tick_marks = np.arange(len(CLASSES))
        plt.xticks(tick_marks, CLASSES, rotation=45)
        plt.yticks(tick_marks, CLASSES)
        for i, j in itertools.product(range(c_m.shape[0]), range(c_m.shape[1])):
            plt.text(j, i, c_m[i, j], horizontalalignment="center", color="white" if c_m[i, j] > (c_m.max()/2.0) else "black")
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
        # PLOT Confusion Matrix with normalization
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.imshow(c_m_norm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=COLOR_MAP)
        plt.title(str(TAG)+" Normalized")
        plt.colorbar()
        tick_marks = np.arange(len(CLASSES))
        plt.xticks(tick_marks, CLASSES, rotation=45)
        plt.yticks(tick_marks, CLASSES)
        for i, j in itertools.product(range(c_m_norm.shape[0]), range(c_m_norm.shape[1])):
            plt.text(j, i, c_m_norm[i, j], horizontalalignment="center", color= \
                "white" if c_m_norm[i, j] > (c_m_norm.max()/2.0) else "black")
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
        # Tight Layout to prevent label overlay
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
    # Draw ROC curve if needed
    if draw_ROC:
        # Calculate False positive rate and True positive rate using data from last RUN
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(test_data_Y.values.ravel(), model.predict_proba(test_data_X)[:,[1]])
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = %0.3f)' % roc_auc)
        plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
        plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
        plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
        plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
        plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
        plt.legend(loc="lower right")
        plt.title("ROC curve of "+str(TAG))
        plt.show()
    
    return ret

# Perform Grid Search
Grid_Result = []
for x in range(0,5):
    Step_Result = []
    for y in range(0,5):
        SVM_model_t = SVC(C=10**x, gamma=0.5**y)
        s = evalute_model(SVM_model_t, RUNS=1, TAG="SVM Model "+str(x)+" "+str(y), data_selection="0100100", SCALE=True)
        print(datetime.now())
        Step_Result.append(s)
    Grid_Result.append(Step_Result)

Some conclusions on classification¶

The choice of attributes¶

  • Gender might have some influence on default payment
  • Education and Marriage does not have so much an influence on default payment
  • Choosing only the History of past payment usually gives the best results in most models, while sex and age will sometimes help

What shall be the lower bound of the score?¶

  • A random guess shall have an accuracy of about 50%
  • A dummy Classifer that respecting the training sets class distribution will have an accuracy of about 65%
  • A dummy Classifer that guess all zeros will have an accuracy of about 77.88%

The fight for Accuracy¶

  • The accuracy is mostly influenced by the indentification of the delay payment entries
  • In most conditions the higher the Recall the better the accuracy
  • We can get a sense of it from the CONFUSION_MATRIX
  • Most Methods can get to a accuracy of 80% after some fine tuning
  • I get at most 82.8% accuracy, using all the methods I tried

Clustering¶

  • I choose to test from K=1 to k=24
  • Gender(2) * Education(4) * Marital status(3) = 24 kinds
  • Education(others) and Marital status(others) only have a percentage of 1% of data
  • Gender(2) * Education(3) * Marital status(2) = 12 kinds
In [14]:
# Clustering Data Pre-process
clustering_data = raw_data[['SEX', 'EDUCATION', 'MARRIAGE']]

# Draw and find the elbow
km_list = []
for i in range(1,25):
    c, l, inertia = k_means(clustering_data, i)
    km_list.append(inertia)
plt.plot(km_list)
plt.annotate('Elbow', xy=(12, km_list[11]), xytext=(12.5, km_list[11]+3000), arrowprops=dict(facecolor='red', shrink=0.1))
plt.show()
  • We can observe the elbow at about k=12
  • Which matches my initial guess since others only show up in a small part of the data
